            <tbody>
               <tr>
                  <td style="padding:0; width:5%;" width="5%">&nbsp;</td>
                  <td class="fallback-font" style="padding: 0; font-weight:normal; font-family: Arial, arial;line-height:22.4px;font-size:14px;color:#363636"><p><span style="font-size: 13pt;"><strong>MUSE 400/546: Surviving the Long Wars: Exploring Parallels Between the US &ldquo;Indian Wars&rdquo; and the &ldquo;Global War on Terror&rdquo;</strong></span><br />Thursdays, 3:30-6:00pm<br />Instructor: Aaron Hughes<br />CRN: 43535 45572<br />Course Description: The UIC Museum and Exhibition Studies Program, UIC Gender and Women&rsquo;s Studies Program, and the emerging Veteran Art Movement are partnering to offer &ldquo;Surviving the Long Wars: Building Discourse and Visualizing Parallels Between the US &ldquo;Indian Wars&rdquo; and the &ldquo;Global War on Terror,&rsquo;&rdquo; a seminar focused on curation of the second Veteran Art Triennial and Summit.<br /><br />During the course student research teams will be partnered with National Endowment for the Humanities Veteran Fellows in order to investigate and build public programs that examine the connections and contradictions between the eighteenth and nineteenth-century US &ldquo;Indian Wars&rdquo; and the twenty-first-century &ldquo;Global War on Terror'' (GWOT). This class will create opportunities for students to deepen their understanding of the experience of war by examining the multiple, overlapping histories that inform contemporary US warfare as well as alternative visions of peace, healing, and justice created by diverse communities. This course will incorporate academic study, curatorial research, and focused group discussions. The course coincides with the &ldquo;New Directions in Comparative Ethnic and Indigenous Studies: Parallels Between the US &ldquo;Indian Wars&rdquo; and the &ldquo;Global War on Terror&rdquo;&mdash;A Virtual Scholarly Seminar and Public Dialogue Series&rdquo; co-curated by Professor Therese Quinn and Professor Ronak K. Kapadia, featuring scholars like Roxanne Dunbar-Ortiz, Kyle Mays, and Laleh Khalili, and it culminates in veteran-led discussion forums at the second Veteran Art Triennial and Summit in Chicago in March 2023.<br /><br /><em>Students are invited but not required to take Part 2 in the Spring.</em></p></td>
                  <td style="padding:0; width:5%;" width="5%">&nbsp;</td>
               </tr>
