      <td>
         <table align="left" bgcolor="#ffffff" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" id="content_31" style="background:transparent; border:none; width:100%; border-spacing:0;">
            <tbody>
               <tr>
                  <td style="padding:0; width:5%;" width="5%">&nbsp;</td>
                  <td class="fallback-font" style="padding: 0; font-weight:normal; font-family: Arial, arial;line-height:22.4px;font-size:14px;color:#363636"><!-- embedded video code start -->
                     <table align="left" style="border-spacing:0;" width="136">
                        <tr>
                           <td><img border="0" src="https://emails.illinois.edu/files/1280676804/processed_2673373.png?p=0510T112726" alt="Woman with brown hair pulled back, wearing a cream v-neck sweater with a green print sleeveless top underneath"></td>
                           <td width="16">&nbsp;</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td height="6" style="height:6px; line-height:6px; font-size:6px;">&nbsp;</td>
                        </tr>
                     </table><!-- embedded video code end --><p><span style="font-size: 13pt;"><strong>Annie "Nicky" Nickum</strong></span><br /><strong>Assistant Professor<br />Information Services &amp; Liaison Librarian</strong><br /><strong>Library Liaison to the UIC Chicago Nursing Community</strong><br /><strong>Library of the Health Sciences</strong><br />Hello! I&rsquo;m Nicky and I am librarian and assistant professor within the University Library at UIC. I have a Bachelor of Science in Nursing from the University of Iowa and a Master&rsquo;s in Library and Information Science from the University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee. Prior to pursuing higher education, I served in the regular army from 2001 to 2005. I started as a linguist then transferred to the medical corps, eventually serving as a pharmacy technician at Fort Leonard Wood, Missouri where I developed a passion for patient education and health literacy.<br /><br />I joined the military right after high school and when I got out, it was a struggle to adapt. I never really knew where to go for help or what was available, so I am committed to assisting others where I can. When I see a student in uniform or hear someone identify as a veteran or military connected, I instantly want to talk to them and see if there&rsquo;s anything I can do to help.<br /><br />As a librarian, it&rsquo;s my job to help people find information. Working with health sciences is especially rewarding because when I teach students how to find resources to provide best practice, I&rsquo;m helping prepare them to be better healthcare practitioners. I&rsquo;m especially interested in what kind of information practicing nurses need to do their jobs, so that I can be sure to give pre-licensure students the tools they&rsquo;ll need. &nbsp;<br /><br />My advice to student veterans is you don&rsquo;t have to go through this alone! The library and all its employees are there to support students and faculty alike. Whether it is locating an item on the shelf or helping navigate the library, we are here to help, and we love to hear about your projects!<br />I hope my role at a veteran in the library has an impact. Representation absolutely matters. Although it&rsquo;s been a while since I served, I remember how overwhelming it was to go from living on a base to attending a large, public university. It&rsquo;s a librarian&rsquo;s job to find information, and I believe that my role and experience uniquely qualify me to understand the questions veteran and military connected students have and to answer them with empathy.</p>
<p>Interested students may contact Annie "Nicky" Nickum&nbsp; at <a style="color: #d50032;" title="Email Annie &lsquo;Nicky&rsquo; Nickum" href="mailto:anicku2@uic.edu" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span style="color: #d50032; font-weight: bold;">anicku2@uic.edu</span></a>.</p></td>
                  <td style="padding:0; width:5%;" width="5%">&nbsp;</td>
               </tr>
            </tbody>
         </table>
      </td>
   </tr>
